==Storylines==
[[Image:JamesWilsonHC.png|thumb|right|250px|Faye leaves her husband for dead in Dubai]]
<!-- ATTENTION! PLEASE READ BEFORE EDITING! Try to keep this section brief. Not every plot detail needs to be added here, especially since the show is currently ongoing. -->
Faye arrives in episode ''Into the Dark'', calling in a favour from [[Specialist registrar|Registrars]] [[Joseph Byrne]] and [[Jac Naylor]], and requesting that they help her gain employment as a [[Nursing_in_the_United_Kingdom#Hierarchy_.26_roles|Bank Nurse]] without her having to give details of her most recent employment records.<ref name="joined">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/holbycity/storyupdates/index.shtml?20070130|title=Episode Update Tuesday 30th Jan|publisher=[[BBC.co.uk]]|date=[[30 January]] [[2007]]|accessdate=2007-08-28}}</ref>  During the first few months of her employment at Holby, Faye remains close to Joseph, but does not get on well with Jac, who she speaks to sternly about her close relationship with Joseph’s father, [[Minor_characters_in_Holby_City#Relatives_2|Lord Byrne]].  In episode ''What Lies Beneath'' , flashbacks occur to the trio’s meeting in [[Dubai]].  Faye’s husband [[Minor_characters_in_Holby_City#Relatives_2|James]] reveals to her than he has lost her life savings of £50,000, ruining her plans of buying a nursing home on England.  The pair fight, and as James forces himself upon her at the top of their staircase, the scene cuts away.  An indefinite period of time later, Faye descends the stairs calmly, and steps over James’s dead body.  It is also revealed that Jac and Joseph performed an operation whilst pretending to be [[Consultant (medicine)|Consultants]], which Faye has been hiding for them since her arrival.  Although she is questioned by police over James’s death, she is not charged.<ref name="wlb">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/holbycity/storyupdates/index.shtml?20070327|title=Episode Update Tuesday 27th Mar|publisher=[[BBC.co.uk]]|date=[[27 March]] [[2007]]|accessdate=2007-08-27}}</ref>

Faye worries her colleagues will find out about her arrest when she is recognised by the [[Minor_characters_in_Holby_City#Relatives_2|Harvey Tyson]], the policeman husband of  AAU‘s [[Nursing_in_the_United_Kingdom#Hierarchy_.26_roles|Acting Sister]] [[Kyla Tyson]].<ref name="3april">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/holbycity/storyupdates/index.shtml?20070403|title=Episode Update Tuesday 3rd Apr|publisher=[[BBC.co.uk]]|date=[[3 April]] [[2007]]|accessdate=2007-08-28}}</ref>  Faye and Kyla strike up a friendship, and supports Kyla through her [[Kyla_Tyson#Domestic_abuse|domestic abuse]] ordeal at the hands of her husband, his subsequent death,<ref name="death">{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/holbycity/storyupdates/index.shtml?20070510|title=Episode Update Tuesday 10th May|publisher=[[BBC.co.uk]]|date= [[10 May]] [[2007]]|accessdate=2007-08-09}}</ref> and the loss of her son to [[foster care]].<ref name="fostercare">{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/holbycity/storyupdates/index.shtml?20070517|title=Episode Update Tuesday 17th May|publisher=[[BBC.co.uk]]|date= [[17 May]] [[2007]]|accessdate=2007-08-09}}</ref>  Also during this period, Faye resists the advances of hospital lothario [[Sam Strachan]],<ref name="6march">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/holbycity/storyupdates/index.shtml?20070306|title=Episode Update Tuesday 6th Mar|publisher=[[BBC.co.uk]]|date=[[6 March]] [[2007]]|accessdate=2007-08-28}}</ref> and impresses General Surgical Consultant [[Daniel Clifford]] with her approach to patient care - leading to an on the spot promotion after a clash with [[Thandie Abebe]] in episode ''Leap of Faith''.<ref name="24april">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/holbycity/storyupdates/index.shtml?20070424|title=Episode Update Tuesday 24th Apr|publisher=[[BBC.co.uk]]|date=[[24 April]] [[2007]]|accessdate=2007-08-27}}</ref>  

Fellow nurse [[Donna Jackson]] aspires to set Faye up with Sam Strachan, and the pair agree to go for a drink.<ref name="31may">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/holbycity/storyupdates/index.shtml?20070531|title=Episode Update Thursday 31st May|publisher=[[BBC.co.uk]]|date=[[31 May]] [[2007]]|accessdate=2007-08-28}}</ref> Faye is the only member of nursing staff not to follow union action in episode ''Countdown'', earning her the approval of [[Connie Beauchamp]], the mother of Sam‘s daughter [[Minor_characters_in_Holby_City#Relatives|Grace]].<ref name="28june">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/holbycity/storyupdates/index.shtml?20070628|title=Episode Update Tuesday 28th Jun|publisher=[[BBC.co.uk]]|date=[[28 June]] [[2007]]|accessdate=2007-08-27}}</ref> In episode ''Damned If You Do'', Sam surprises Faye with a gift of a diamond necklace, with which she is delighted, however she is unaware that Sam has the ulterior motive of wanting to get out of a weekend break with her in favour of attending a cricket match with his friends.  Later in the same episode, he kisses old flame [[Chrissie Williams]] when she admits she still has feelings for him.<ref name="14august">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/holbycity/storyupdates/index.shtml?20070814|title=Episode Update Tuesday 14th Aug|publisher=[[BBC.co.uk]]|date=[[14 August]] [[2007]]|accessdate=2007-08-28}}</ref>

==Reception==
===Popularity===
[[Image:FayeMortonRT.jpg|thumb|left|100px|Radio Times]]
Although the character only arrived on the show on [[30 January]] [[2007]], in [[May]] [[2007]] [[Patsy Kensit]] was shortlisted for the ''Best Actress'' award in the [[2007]] [[TV Quick]] and TV Choice Awards for her portrayal of the character.<ref name="award">{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20070524095225/http://www.tvchoiceawards.co.uk/|title=2007 TV Quick & TV Choice Awards|publisher=[[TV Quick]]|date=[[May]] [[2007]]|accessdate=2007-08-11}}</ref>

While [[Holby City]] usually averages around 5.5 million viewers per week,<ref name="hcviewing">{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/viewingsummary/weekreports.cfm?report=weeklyterrestrial&RequestTimeout=500|title=	
Weekly Viewing Summary|publisher=[[BARB]]|accessdate=2007-08-10}}</ref> the two episodes most pivotal to the character to date have averaged much higher. ''What Lies Beneath'', the [[flashback]] episode in which the character was seen to kill her husband in [[Dubai]] drew ratings of 6.32 million.<ref name="wlbrating">{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/viewingsummary/weekreports.cfm?report=weeklyterrestrial&RequestTimeout=500|title=	
Weekly Viewing Summary w/e 01/04/2007|publisher=[[BARB]]|accessdate=2007-08-10}}</ref> The character's introductory episode, ''Into the Dark'' drew an unusually high 7 million viewers,<ref name="itd">{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/viewingsummary/weekreports.cfm?report=weeklyterrestrial&RequestTimeout=500|title=	
Weekly Viewing Summary w/e 04/02/2007|publisher=[[BARB]]|accessdate=2007-08-10}}</ref> explained to some extent by the higher than average amount of publicity this episode received as a result of [[Patsy Kensit|Kensit]] joining the cast - including a front cover and inside spread in the week's edition of the [[Radio Times]].<ref name="rt">{{Citation
 | last=
 | first=
 | author-link=
 | publication-date=[[3 February]] - [[9 February]] [[2007]]
 | date=
 | year=
 | title=Patsy Plays Nurse
 | periodical=[[Radio Times]]
 | publication-place=[[England]]
 | place=
 | publisher=
 | volume=
 | issue=
 | pages=
 | url=
 | doi=
 | oclc=
 | accessdate=
}}</ref>

The character has continued to receive higher amounts of publicity than usually attracted by Holby City characters.  The [[11 August]] [[2007]] edition of Total TV Guide featured Kensit, [[Tina Hobley]] and [[Tom Chambers]] on its front cover, appearing in character to promote their [[love triangle]] storyline.  It was also reported on [[19 August]] [[2007]] that the introduction of the character and Kensit's joining the cast has 'boosted the series' appeal',<ref name="calendar">{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.excite.co.uk/news/soaps/41764|title=	
Holby City calendar may be on cards|publisher=[[Excite]]|date=[[19 August]] [[2007]]|accessdate=2007-08-26}}</ref> to such an extent that for the first time, a Holby City calendar has been commissioned.  The report stated that 'An insider said: "Patsy has really set the show off this year, and what better way to thank the dedicated fans?"'<ref name="calendar">{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.excite.co.uk/news/soaps/41764|title=	
Holby City calendar may be on cards|publisher=[[Excite]]|date=[[19 August]] [[2007]]|accessdate=2007-08-26}}</ref>

===Criticism===
[[Image:FayeMortonNMC.jpg|thumb|right|100px|NMC magazine]]
The character of Faye specifically, and all the nursing staff characters in [[Holby City]] generally came under heavy criticism in the [[July]] [[2007]] edition of the [[Nursing and Midwifery Council]] magazine.<ref name="nmc">{{Citation
 | last=Jaegar
 | first=Andy
 | author-link=
 | publication-date=[[July]] [[2007]]
 | date=
 | year=
 | title=Stitched Up? The portrayal of nurses in popular culture.
 | periodical=[[Nursing and Midwifery Council]] Magazine
 | publication-place=[[England]]
 | place=
 | publisher=
 | volume=
 | issue=21
 | pages=30
 | url=
 | doi=
 | oclc=
 | accessdate=
}}</ref> The publication discussed the topic of nurses in popular culture, and the negative impression of the nursing profession conveyed by fictional nurses.  With a promotional image of [[Patsy Kensit|Kensit]] as Faye adorning the front cover, the magazine asserted:
:"The "did she, didn't she", story of the Dubai murder of Faye Morton's partner in Holby City recently demonstrates the ease with which writers can attach terrible storylines to a caring profession. Nurses who become prostitutes to pay the bills, nurses who kill their husbands, nurses who abuse the system to get their own way - Holby City has always been a hotbed of slanderous storylines. Good people doing bad things makes excellent entertainment... The bald fact is that real life nurses doing their jobs well just aren't that entertaining."<ref name="nmc">{{Citation
 | last=Jaegar
 | first=Andy
 | author-link=
 | publication-date=[[July]] [[2007]]
 | date=
 | year=
 | title=Stitched Up? The portrayal of nurses in popular culture.
 | periodical=[[Nursing and Midwifery Council]] Magazine
 | publication-place=[[England]]
